<br>
I guess we'll just have a difference of opinion on this one, because I still fail to see Starbucks, the corporation, as doing wrong in this situation.  For me, this situation, like many others, goes back to one statement:<br>
<br>
Under no circumstances (even as horrific as the WTC bombing), can one man's need justify a claim on another man's (or entity's) ability (including money, resources, etc.).<br>
<br>
While I, like most people in this country, would have given the worker the water, that is a decision I make for myself.  For me to say that a person or business must 'give' away their resources, regardless of cause, would make me a communist.<br>
<br>
Did they make a bad business decision by not rectifying the situation immediately?  Probably.  But it was well within their moral rights to charge for the water IMHO.  If consumers want to penalize them for not giving away water, that is their right, but I really do think folks should think about the statement above first...<br>
<br>
Not to anyone in particular,<br>
If anyone has a problem understanding the implications of what happens when one man's need IS allowed to present a claim on another man, think slavery, it's really that simple.<br>
<br>
Gar<br>
<br>
PS.  Back to Cao, hehe, if they hadn't had the money, they probably would have gone to another establishment that wouldn't have charged them.  When people need something badly enough, they find a way to get it, in my experience. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uraedwulf.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Raedwulf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 313<br> <font color=#E9D756>(10/5/01 9:42:31 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=209.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Well...</span><hr size=1> The Starbucks' lackey made a bad decision.  He's a fucking cashier, not someone used to making business and marketting decisions, and he made the wrong one.<br>
<br>
When Starbucks Customer Service was contacted, they clearly thought the story sounded so incredibly dumb, that they didn't believe it.  Again, front line customer service folks don't have a lot of authority, and aren't used to making such decisions.  <br>
<br>
My wife used to manage a customer service department for a mega-bank, and the folks that answer the phone usually can't find their ass with both hands.  That's why I always ask for a supervisor.  Usually you won't really get one, but at least you are more likely to get one of the sharper folks on the floor or get your request moved up in the cue.<br>
<br>
Starbucks made a big mistake.  Well, two of their dimmer employees did.  Blaming the whole company for the mistakes of a few high school grads is hardly fair. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ucaoilfhionn.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Caoilfhionn</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_fire.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Erotic, exotic & a little psychotic</span><br>  Posts: 541<br> <font color=#E9D756>(10/5/01 3:39:12 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=209.topic&index=8>Reply</a>    <br>Community Supporter<br> <BR><img src=http://www.altdzin.com/tgl/cao.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Well...</span><hr size=1> blaming the company for the actions of it's employees is MORE than fair.<br>
