ic</span><br>  Posts: 547<br> <font color=#E9D756>(10/6/01 10:48:45 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=209.topic&index=10>Reply</a>    <br>Community Supporter<br> <BR><img src=http://www.altdzin.com/tgl/cao.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Well...</span><hr size=1> you missed a point, Raed.<br>
<br>
Journalists *CALLED* starbucks about the situation and were ignored.  It was not until massive amounts of media and email targetted the actions of the company that they decided to fix it.<br>
<br>
What I dislike about their actions is this:<br>
<br>
It should have been corrected because they felt the wrong action had been taken rather than a media blitz forcing them to take action and correct it for fear of &quot;not looking good&quot;<br>
<br>
I don't blame the action of the cashier, re-read my posts.  He did what he thought he had to do, it's not what I would have done, but he made a choice, based on how he perceived his company would want him to act.<br>
<br>
I work in a company that has a huge customer service base.  In fact, I provide the training and the knowledge that they take to the lines with them.  Take it from me, everyone who leaves my class after knows damn well if they told someone &quot;that would never happen&quot; and dismissing a complaint would find themselves jobless in a minute.<br>
<br>
But, even dismissing the actions of the cashier, and forgiving the stupidity of the CS rep, the fact remains that other folks went straight to the PR dept and the president and didn't get a response til news reports were actually published.  <br>
<br>
Shame, Starbucks could have resolved this much earlier than they did, they chose not to until it had the potential to make them look bad.<br>
